"Chapter 1\n\nDusk bled streaks of orange and violet across the rolling green of the course. Through the low mist, the rhythmic thud of bodies on the grass echoed—a pulse beneath my boots. Shadows stretched between ancient oaks and the manicured fairways that now served as obstacles; this was not the world I’d left behind. My fingers found the cold metal of my wristwatch.\n\nToo late to turn back, not now. Behind me, a small group watched intently. The name on the weathered sign above them read, in bold letters, . I adjusted the lanyard around my neck, catching a glimpse of my own name—though I dared not look closely. Bethpage Black Course. Ezra Edwards. Demonstrated cat leaps.\n\nSomeone in the crowd, face half-turned in the gathering gloom, whispered with awe. “He’s really doing it,” Noa Middleton said, breathless. I knew they were referring to me, though no one had said the word yet. My coach had promised today I’d “show the cat leap again,” but I wondered if I was ready for their eyes to see it in a new way.\n\nThe instructor, tall and wiry with a shaved head and a perpetual look of intent, gestured for me to step onto the first wall. The surface was cold stone, slightly rough under my palms. A thin wind picked up, tangling strands of hair against my neck and heightening the tension in my shoulders. The crowd leaned forward, a murmur of anticipation that prickled through the fading light.\n\nMy mind raced: technique, safety, the thin thread between mastery and disaster. Every muscle tightened as the instructor called out, “Three, two, one—Ezra!” The leap was meant to be fluid—a cat bounding from a ledge with effortless grace. But I felt the old prickle, that moment before gravity’s claim. I rolled onto my knees, braced against the stone, and pushed off.\n\nThe world tilted, grass rushing upward, the scent of damp earth filling my lungs. My arms stretched—muscles burning, focus narrowing—then, a sudden, exhilarating suspension as the ground slipped away beneath m