ished analyses, the heavy silence of unmet expectations. Outside, the city’s morning traffic rushed on. Completed peer review.\n\n\nChapter 105\n\nThe scent of sun-warmed asphalt and faint whiffs of lavender drifted on the summer evening as Isaiah made his way through the trees, their green boughs swaying gently in the July breeze. Laughter flickered from an open clearing—musical, not quite human—echoing beneath the hushed roar of late afternoon clouds.\n\nHis pulse quickened at the sight of shimmering fabrics, glinting under the park’s wide, scattered lights. This was not just a gathering of friends, he realized; the air felt charged with anticipation, like a scene before the curtain. July 21, 2024.\n\nTime seemed to fold on the clock faces around him; somewhere nearby, someone had set an old radio to the dot of a waltz, but the sound was eclipsed by the rising crescendo of movement. Above, a white-painted gazebo stood half-lit by string lamps strung between ancient oaks, their roots tangled beneath the stage-like ground.\n\nThe sky burned with the lazy gold of late summer, a backdrop for the unfolding spectacle he’d engineered with quiet ambition. He followed the throng of bodies toward the center, where costumed performers began to assemble, their faces hidden by extravagant makeup, feathers, and sequins.\n\nThe first performer, in a high-collared, midnight blue ensemble, stretched languidly as the spotlight traced the curves of her silhouette. A hush fell again, and Isaiah caught the faint rustle of his own breath in his chest—a self-scrutinizing tension he couldn’t quite explain.\n\nA woman beside him, draped in a dark scarf and watching intently, shifted as the next performer emerged. The stage lights dimmed to a smoky amber, then snapped to scarlet, illuminating a figure in exaggerated crimson and black, hips swaying with practiced ease. Isaiah Bennett.\n\nEvery movement was calculated, each gesture echoing an old silent film’s seductiveness—yet there was a r